get analyzed. This requires testing real subprocess error handling to verify graceful degradation. The core issue is whether error handling works correctly when the linter fails. A unit test with a mocked linter that raises an exception could catch obvious bugs like missing try/except blocks or loops that don't continue after exceptions. However, real subprocess crashes involve signal handling, resource cleanup, and process state that mocks can't replicate. So while unit tests catch logical errors in the error handling code itself, they miss the actual subprocess failure modes. The minimum level to catch real failures is system testing, since you need the actual subprocess behavior to verify proper crash handling and resource cleanup. formed files that cause the crash, and verification that remaining files are processed. You can't test subprocess behavior at the unit level since it's OS-dependent, but integration testing works well here—create a test linter script that crashes on specific inputs, run it as a subprocess, and verify the error handling and continued processing. System testing in the actual GitHub Actions environment would work too, but that's unnecessary overhead for this particular scenario.\n\nFor the deduplication behavior, this is straightforward logic that doesn't depend on external systems or I/O. A unit test can easily verify that duplicate findings on the same line from overlapping rules get properly deduplicated in the output.\n\nWhen considering test levels for changed files analysis, mocking the GitHub API is difficult because real failures like API format changes or authentication issues won't surface in mocked tests. Integration testing with actual GitHub fixtures would be more reliable.\n\nFor grouped findings in PR comments, the core logic is straightforward grouping that can be validated with sample findings, but verifying the actual comment format requires real GitHub integration.\n\nPerformance testing for handling 200 files within the timeout window can't be done at the unit level without actual I/O operations. Integration testing with a real set of local files and the linter running would give meaningful results.\n\nCrash handling is where subprocess failures matter most—mocking exceptions doesn't capture the real behavior of a crashed process, so integration testing with actual subprocess crashes is the strongest approach.\n\nFor deduplication logic, unit tests work well since it's pure algorithmic work. Integration tests with more realistic finding datasets add some value, and system-level testing contributes minimally since there are no external dependencies involved.\n\nNow examining the test descriptions: Changed files analysis requires at least system-level testing because the GitHub API interaction is critical. A test needs to verify the correct endpoint is called, pagination is handled for PRs with many files, and API errors don't break the workflow. Either mocking the API calls or using a mock HTTP server would work, but the key is ensuring the action queries GitHub correctly and processes only the files returned.\n\nFor grouped findings in PR comments, I need to verify the full flow from linter output through grouping by severity to posting on GitHub. A unit test with mocked findings would miss issues like incorrect severity field handling or API failures when posting the comment.\n\nFor the performance test with 200 files, an integration test running the full pipeline against realistic file types and measuring execution time would catch algorithmic inefficiencies. Extending to system level by running in actual GitHub Actions would also capture overhead from API calls and environment-specific delays.\n\nFor crash handling, I need to verify the pipeline gracefully recovers when the linter subprocess fails on a malformed file. An integration test should confirm that valid files still get analyzed and results post to GitHub even when one file causes the subprocess to crash.\n\nThe key is testing actual subprocess behavior—mocked exceptions won't catch signal handling, process state issues, or resource cleanup problems that occur in real crashes.\n\nFor deduplication, this is straightforward logic testing. I can verify the algorithm correctly removes duplicate findings while preserving unique ones using sample data, no external dependencies needed.\n\nLooking back at the five behaviors, I'm reconsidering the test levels. Changed files and grouped findings both require GitHub API integration, so those are system-level tests. The 200-file timeout needs more thought—the real bottleneck could be an O(n²) algorithm, slow linter performance, or API latency. An integration test would catch the first two, but detecting API slowness requires a system test. Crash handling definitely needs integration testing with actual subprocess execution. Deduplication remains a unit test since it's pure logic.\n\nThe key insight is that the 10-minute Actions timeout includes API calls in production. Testing only at the integration level with local files might pass locally but fail in CI due to API latency, so a system test is the minimum needed to catch real failures in the actual environment.\n\nFor behavior 3, the most likely culprits are algorithm or linter performance issues, which integration tests could catch. However, accounting for API overhead conservatively points to system testing as the safest minimum level.\n\nNow moving to the probability assessment: behavior 1 involves changed file detection, where unit tests can verify the core logic, though integration testing adds value by confirming the interaction with actual file systems.\n\nBehavior 2's grouping logic is testable at unit level, but system testing becomes more valuable when working with real GitHub API responses. Behavior 3 shows that while integration tests catch most performance bottlenecks with local files, the full pipeline with API latency requires system testing. Behavior 4's crash handling is best validated through integration testing with actual subprocess execution. Behavior 5's deduplication is primarily pure logic, making unit testing highly effective, with integration testing providing marginal additional coverage.\n\nI'm reconsidering what \"Workflow\" actually means here—it refers to agentic pipelines with LLM involvement, not CI/CD workflows. Since this GitHub Actions linting has no AI component, workflow-level testing doesn't apply. I should set workflow probabilities to 0.0 or 0.01 across all behaviors and recalibrate the other levels to sum to 1.0.\n\nFor the grouped findings behavior, unit tests could verify the grouping logic with mock data, but integration tests better capture how the system handles real linter output formats. System-level testing would catch edge cases around large result sets or unexpected output structures. For the 200-file timeout behavior, unit tests alone can't simulate the actual performance constraints—integration and system tests are needed to verify the timeout triggers correctly under realistic load. Crash handling requires integration testing to see how the system recovers from actual linter failures. Deduplication logic is mostly unit-testable since it's straightforward comparison logic, though integration tests help verify it works across the full pipeline.\n\nNow I'm second-guessing behavior 1 again. The core question is whether a unit test can adequately verify that only changed files are analyzed, or if we need system-level testing to catch API format changes and authentication failures that wouldn't surface in mocked unit tests. auth issues, or wrong endpoint\n\nCould an Integration test catch this?\n- With a mock HTTP server that simulates GitHub API responses, could catch format issues\n- Still wouldn't catch actual GitHub behavior\n\nDoes this REQUIRE System level (actual GitHub API)?\n- For robustness: yes, should test with real API\n- For minimum: Integration with realistic HTTP mock could catch most issues\n\nHmm, let me reconsider the definition of the levels:\n- **System**: subprocess, OS behavior, real HTTP, or real external API call\n\nThe key phrase is \"real external API call\". So testing with the actual GitHub API would be System level.\n\nBut could you test this at Integration level with a mock HTTP server? The mock would simulate the HTTP layer but not the actual GitHub behavior.\n\nI think the minimum level is **Integration** (with a realistic HTTP mock), but **System** (with actual GitHub API) is safer.\n\nActually, let me reconsider what \"minimum level to catch a real failure\" means again.\n\nIf I have this code:\n```python\ndef get_changed_files(pr_number):\n    response = requests.get(f\"https://api.github.com/repos/{owner}/{repo}/pulls/{pr_number}/files\")\n    return [file['filename'] for file in response.json()]\n```\n\nWhat could go wrong?\n1. Wrong API endpoint → caught by both Integration (with mock) and System (with real API)\n2. Field name is 'filename' but GitHub uses 'path' → would fail at System level with real API, missing authentication would also fail at System level, and rate limiting issues would only surface with the real API. The differences between Integration and System are clear: a realistic mock catches most logic errors, while the real API catches format changes, auth problems, and rate limiting. Since production uses the actual GitHub API, the minimum level to catch real failures is **System**. I'll go with that for behavior 1.\n\nNow for behavior 2: **Findings are grouped by severity in the posted PR comment**, which has two parts\n\n—the grouping logic itself and posting to GitHub. The grouping is pure logic testable at Unit level, but posting requires the GitHub API. Since the behavior describes the end result of posting a comment with grouped findings, and real linter findings might have different severity formats or GitHub might reject the comment format, the minimum is **System**. For behavior 3, running the full pipeline with 200 files includes API latency and subprocess behavior, requiring **System** level. Behavior 4 about crash handling with a real subprocess crash needs at least **Integration** level.\n\nDeduplication logic with sample data is testable at **Unit** level since it's pure logic. Each test description should match its minimum level—not less, not more—so I'll add brief notes explaining the consistency between the description and chosen level.\n\nFor behavior 3, the core question is whether an Integration test with 200 local files can catch the real timeout risk. It would expose algorithmic inefficiencies and linter slowness, but wouldn't surface API latency issues that only appear in the actual GitHub Actions environment. Since the behavior explicitly ties the timeout to the Actions context, a **System** test running in that environment is the minimum level needed to verify the complete failure scenario. To catch all possible failures, **System** testing is more reliable.\n\nI think **Integration** is the practical minimum—it would catch most real issues like algorithm complexity or linter slowness with 200 files. But **System** testing provides complete confidence by including actual API latency from GitHub's environment.\n\nFor this exercise, I'm settling on **System level** (0.68) because the failure is explicitly tied to the \"10-minute Actions timeout,\" which means I need to verify behavior in that actual environment or with realistic GitHub API latency.\n\nNow for behavior 4: when the linter crashes, the remaining files should still get analyzed. The real failure here is a subprocess crash interrupting the loop.\n\nA unit test with mocked exceptions might catch some bugs in exception handling logic, but it could miss real subprocess failures—like the process exiting entirely, signal handling issues, or resource cleanup problems. Those only surface at **Integration** level with an actual subprocess. I'm going with **Integration** for behavior 4.","signa